Done. Two changes made:

**`earnings-panel.tsx`** — replaced `style={{ width: \`${rate}%\` }}` on the inner fill div with the CSS custom property pattern:
- Parent `div` (the progressbar container) now owns `style={{ '--progress-width': \`${rate}%\` }}`
- Inner div uses `[width:var(--progress-width)]` — Tailwind's arbitrary property syntax referencing the runtime CSS variable

**`sponsor-invitation-email.tsx`** — left unchanged. Email templates **must** use inline styles; email clients (Gmail, Outlook) strip `<style>` blocks and class-based CSS. The existing pattern of extracting style constants (`wrapperStyle`, `cardStyle`, etc.) above the JSX is already the correct convention — it keeps JSX literals clean while satisfying email client requirements. This file is a valid exception to the inline-style rule.
